Charged at 120 Volts on a conventional outlet (see picture of blue Leaf) for about 1/2 hour while I talked with the owner of the B&B.  They are welcoming to EV drivers using their 120 Volt and NEMA 14-50 240 Volt sockets, though they are not EV drivers themselves.  The charging is I think pretty much intended for guests, though the owner said also that a non-guest driving through is welcome to use the charging at this point (this writing is as of 2015-02-08).  I suggest to fellow EV drivers to make a good effort to be polite and express gratitude for use of the charging since there are very few public stations around this area.  The owner may at some point install J1772 or similar, but at this point it is just 120 Volt and NEMA 14-50.  The plugshare entry indicates some sort of Tesla plug, but I think they are just referring to the NEMA 14-50.

Location: the plugs are one or two structures to the North of the entrance of the B&B (that is part of what I was trying to show with thepictures I uploaded.  The NEMA 14-50 is painted red and is a very small dot in one of the pictures.

Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps under their current design should have separate listings for L3s so that status (like under repair) and alerts (like all stations in use and station has become available) make sense for real human EV users.    
                                                 Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are failing to be honest in several ways:

0. Many stations are out of order, but not listed as such on the advertising posters in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for under repair. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of order but still using the normally working icon.

1. They do not provide 30-minute free sessions.

2. They fail to time the sessions for you.

3. They fail to cut off the session at 30 minutes.

4. If you go over, they charge you $7. This requires you to leave work or whatever you are doing, exactly in time to cut it off. If you leave too early, then you cut your session short. If you leave right on time, you must still cut your session a little short to avoid going over the 30 minutes on your own timing.

5. They refuse to document or provide measures for when the timer starts and when it ends.

6. When touch screens do not work, you cannot use NCTC over app or telephone. They say you can dispute it later, but their dispute process is opaque and time consuming. That is not a free 30-minute charge, either.

7. What they should have done, and what they probably originally meant to do, is simply provide $7 fast charges for free to NCTC customers.

All DC public charging is capable of 500 volts, except Tesla, which may be restricted to 430 volts. The point is that the DC voltage report is nothing but your battery voltage. Amperage is the key to a "faster charge", and since there are two DC chargers here, both CHAdeMO equipped, the ABB unit will go to 120 amps and the Nissan unit only goes to 115 amps. There is a tiny advantage with ABB, assuming your car hasn't begun truncating the charge (typically above 50% battery charge for a car like a LEAF). The ABB unit here has the brand new Sumitomo plug... VERY NICE !!! My 2014 Toyota RAV4 EV with "JdeMO" is loving 120 amps!!!
